Interface Value

All Superinterfaces:
Data
All Known Subinterfaces:
AttributeValue, Contained, Container, DataValue, EnumValue, LinkEnd, ObjectValue, Reference
All Known Implementing Classes:
ValueImpl
public interface Value
extends Data

This interface represents a value in the framework object model. XMIObjects have values that are defined by the features in the corresponding XMIClass. The XMI name of a value is the XMI name of a feature in an XMIClass.

If the value is an attribute value, the type is either Value.DATA, Value.ENUM, or Value.OBJECT, based on the corresponding attribute's type. If the type of the attribute is an enumeration, the type of the value is Value.ENUM. If the type of the attribute is a datatype, the type of the value is Value.DATA. If the type of the attribute is a class, the type of the value is Value.OBJECT.

If the value is a link end, the type is either Value.REFERENCE, Value.CONTAINER, or Value.CONTAINED, based on the aggregation property of an association end. If the corresponding association end is across from an association end whose aggregation property is composition, the value type is Value.CONTAINED. If the corresponding association end has an aggregation property of composition, the value type is Value.CONTAINER. If the corresponding association end has no composition semantics, the value type is Value.REFERENCE.

Each value object may represent one or more values. The XMI value of a Value object is either a String, an XMIObject, or a Collection containing either Strings or XMIObjects. If the XMI type of the value is Value.DATA or Value.ENUM, the value of the Value object is either a String or Collection containing Strings. If the XMI type of the value is either Value.OBJECT, Value.CONTAINED, Value.CONTAINER, or Value.REFERENCE, the value of the Value object is either an XMIObject or Collection or XMIObjects.

The XMI value of a Value object may be null.

It is illegal for two values to be added to an object if the values have the same XMI name.
